\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN2}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Entitlement as Matter of Law, Genuine Disputes}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 A court shall grant summary judgment if the movant shows that there is no genuine dispute as to any material fact and the movant is entitled to judgment as a matter of law. }{\f5\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 Fed. R. Civ. P. 56(a)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 .}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Civil Procedure\~>\~...\~>\~Summary Judgment\~>\~Motions for Summary Judgment\~>\~Cross Motions}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN3}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Motions for Summary Judgment, Cross Motions}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Where courts are presented with cross-motions for summary judgment, they must view each motion separately, in the light most favorable to the non-moving party, and draw all reasonable inferences in that party's favor.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~Discrimination\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Scope & Definitions}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN4}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Title VII makes it unlawful for an employer to fail or refuse to hire or to discharge any individual, or otherwise to discriminate against any individual with respect to his compensation, terms, conditions, or privileges of employment, because of such individual's religion. }{\f5\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.S. \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e-2(a)(1)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . The term religion includes all aspects of religious observance and practice, as well as belief, unless an employer demonstrates that he is unable to reasonably accommodate an employee's or prospective employee's religious observance or practice without undue hardship on the conduct of the employer's business. }{\f5\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.S. \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e(j)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . Title VII, thus, requires that an employer, short of undue hardship, make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of its employees.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Burdens of Proof\~>\~Burden Shifting}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Burdens of Proof\~>\~Employee Burdens}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN5}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Burdens of Proof, Burden Shifting}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 A version of the McDonnell Douglas burden-shifting analysis aids courts in addressing failure to accommodate religious practices questions. At the first step of that analysis, it is the employee's burden to establish a prima facie claim by showing that 1) the employee has a bona fide religious belief that conflicts with a job requirement, 2) the employee informed the employer of this conflict; and 3) the employer fired the employee for failing to comply with the job requirement.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN6}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Title VII requires that an employer, short of undue hardship, make reasonable accommodations to the religious needs of its employees. Accommodate means allowing the plaintiff to engage in her religious practice despite the employer's normal rules to the contrary.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN7}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 To be reasonable, a religious accommodation need not provide a total accommodation. Although an employee is not required to modify his religious beliefs, a reasonable accommodation need not be on the employee's terms, only.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN8}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Any reasonable religious accommodation by the employer is sufficient to meet its accommodation obligation. An employee is not entitled to the accommodation of his choice. Once the employer has provided a reasonable accommodation, it need not further show that each of the employee's alternative accommodations would result in undue hardship.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN9}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Title VII expressly requires only that an employer reasonably accommodate an employee's religion, }{\f5\fs28\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 42 U.S.C.S. \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u167\'A7 2000e(j)}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 . Determining what is reasonable is a fact-specific determination that must be made on a case-by-case basis.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN10}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Title VII does not demand mere neutrality with regard to religious practices\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 that they be treated no worse than other practices. Rather, it gives them favored treatment, affirmatively obligating employers not to fail or refuse to hire or discharge any individual because of such individual's religious observance and practice. An employer is surely entitled to have, for example, a no-headwear policy as an ordinary matter. But when an applicant requires an accommodation as an aspect of religious practice, it is no response that the subsequent failure to hire was due to an otherwise-neutral policy. Title VII requires otherwise-neutral policies to give way to the need for an accommodation.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN11}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 An employer cannot take refuge behind a neutral policy if something more is required reasonably to accommodate a religious need. An employer can, of course, meet its obligation to accommodate its employees' religious practice by using a neutral policy, so long as that policy reasonably accommodates the employee's religious needs. Nothing in Title VII requires the accommodation uniquely to target a religious concern. But, on the other hand, if a general policy does not amount to a reasonable accommodation of the employee's religious needs, then merely having a neutral employment policy will not absolve the employer of its Title VII obligation reasonably to accommodate its employee's religious practices, short of an undue hardship. Were that not so, the 'reasonable accommodation requirement could not accomplish its intended objective. Title VII requires otherwise-neutral policies to give way to the need for an accommodation.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN12}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Subject to a reasonableness analysis, an employee may be required to use vacation or other paid time off to avoid conflict with religious obligations.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN13}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Defenses, Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 An employee has a duty to cooperate with his employer's attempts to accommodate the employee's religious practices.}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24
\par\pard\plain \li360\ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Civil Procedure\~>\~...\~>\~Summary Judgment\~>\~Entitlement as Matter of Law\~>\~Need for Trial}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Labor & Employment Law\~>\~...\~>\~Religious Discrimination\~>\~Defenses\~>\~Reasonable Accommodation & Undue Hardship}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 Civil Procedure\~>\~Trials\~>\~Jury Trials\~>\~Province of Court & Jury}
\par\pard\plain \ri-1600\sb240\sl260\slmult0\qj\ltrch\loch {\f4\fs28\b1\i1\ul\ulc0\cf4\cb2\highlight2 HN14}{\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1  }{\f3\fs28\b1\i0\cf1 \~Entitlement as Matter of Law, Need for Trial}
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b0\i0\cf1 An employer incurs an undue hardship if it must bear more than a de minimis cost in order to give an employee Saturdays off to observe his Sabbath. Any cost in efficiency or wage expenditure that is more than de minimis constitutes undue hardship. The cost of hiring an additional worker or the loss of production that results from not replacing a worker who is unavailable due to a religious conflict can amount to undue hardship. It is the employer's burden to show that it cannot offer a reasonable accommodation without undue hardship. Whether an employer will incur an undue hardship is a fact question that turns on the particular factual context of each case.}
